      {
        "Header": "Act One",
        "Text": "Kirk orders McCoy to give Charlie a thorough physical and begins the process of integrating him into shipboard life. Charlie tries to imitate adult behavior he observes but misunderstands boundaries and personal space, especially with Rand. He presents her with an inappropriate gift and struggles when crew members laugh or correct him. While Charlie seems desperate to please, there are subtle hints of something more: people sense unease around him, and the Antares crew’s earlier tension remains unexplained."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act Two",
        "Text": "News arrives that the Antares has been destroyed soon after leaving the Enterprise. Charlie claims to know it was due to a mechanical problem, even though he could not logically have that information. When a crewman teases him in the gym, Charlie makes the man's legs vanish for a moment and then restores them, treating the act as a lesson rather than an attack. He begins altering reality around him: silencing people, manipulating objects, and making anyone who embarrasses him simply disappear. Kirk and Spock grow increasingly certain that Charlie has formidable psionic abilities tied to his emotional outbursts."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act Three",
        "Text": "Kirk tries to teach Charlie discipline, setting limits and insisting that he cannot always get what he wants, particularly where Rand is concerned. Charlie resents any restriction and becomes more controlling, seizing voice functions, transforming food in the galley, and twisting crew members' bodies and faces as punishment. After Rand gently rejects his romantic advances, Charlie lashes out and makes her vanish altogether. With fear spreading through the ship, Kirk realizes that conventional force cannot stop Charlie and looks instead for a way to overtax his abilities or appeal to some authority greater than his."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act Four",
        "Text": "Kirk attempts to overload Charlie by forcing him to juggle the full systems load of the Enterprise while the crew resists him, hoping the strain will weaken his control. Instead, Charlie doubles down, declaring that he owns the ship and everyone on it. A mysterious alien vessel then appears: a Thasian ship, whose non-corporeal inhabitants gave Charlie his powers so he could survive alone on their harsh world. They restore the Enterprise and her crew to normal and insist that Charlie must return with them because he is too dangerous to live among humans. Charlie pleads desperately to stay, terrified of losing the human contact he has only just discovered, but the Thasians remove him. The Enterprise resumes course, leaving behind a sense of tragic inevitability rather than triumph."
